 this spell is where is the risk that is supposed to be associated in charming?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Reports so far suggest that the cost and risk is in practice ordinary.  In my crude estimate, it would take a significant amount of risk, perhaps as much as 50% fatality per encounter and maybe more, to balance it.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Zyphanus:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  If you increase risk however, you run the chance of making the ability useless. Enchanters would then find no use at all from charming, which is a major spell-line that they rely upon.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Absolutely.  Charm is both an important form of crowd control, and a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>jujitsu</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->-like technique to turn the strength of the enemy back upon them.  It is and should remain very powerful.<br>
<br>
Factors that can be addressed include:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Risk:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> How likely is it to result in death or wipeout?<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Cost:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> How much effort does it take to start and sustain it?<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Potency:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> How powerful are the charmed mobs?<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Applicability:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> How available are appropriate charmable mobs?<br>
<br>
So risk could be moderately increased, more mana or other support could be required, charmed mobs might have reduced damage output, or mobs could be flagged for resistance to charm <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(flagged mobs being the traditional bane of enchanters everywhere)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Zyphanus:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Pre-POP, charm was a powerful ability but no one cried about its brokenness so it stands to reason that PoP itself is at the root of the problem. When examining the new charm spells, they seem to scale correctly and nothing about the spell itself has changed. What HAS changed is the type of monsters.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Yes.  Charmed PoP mobs have very high DPS.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Zyphanus:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Even though I'm not an advocate of nerfs usually, I think scaling all other classes' power up accordingly would be even worse.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->That it how it seems to me as well.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Zyphanus:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  I liked the suggestions with keeping the dependability of charm but having a long recast timer<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->This strikes me as an elegent proposal, and reinforces the existing distinctions between summoned and charmed pets.  Summoned pets are more available, but charmed pets are more powerful.  Lowering the availability of the best charmed pets by a long recast delay on the best charms seems among the least intrusive remedies I have seen yet.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Mandryke:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  ...a very simple solution to this...if you charm a NPC that hits for 350-700 max hit, it then hits while charmed at a capped max of say mid 200's<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->That is also clean, but robs enchanters the joy of charming some major buttkick .  The advantage of reducing availability instead of damage output is that it preserves enchanter ability while resisting abuse.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>TheDwellerInDarkness:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  I think one of the best ways to balance Charms are to give them very long recast times, greater than max duration. When an enchanter is charming stuff much lower level then he can obviously alternate between charms, using the proper one and a higher level one as well. This will eat mana up faster for a relativley lower level pet, but make it possible to chain charm. When he charms a higher level mob, presumably he has only the one charm appropriate to use, and he know he will not have a chance to recharm after break, making him much more dependant on a FULL group.... feel these changes will allow enchanters to continue to use charm in much the same way they always have, maintains it's &quot;wow&quot; factor of a heavy hitting high hitpoint pet, but doesn't allow for an enchanter to string charm massively powerful pets making other classes useless. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Very well said and reasoned.  Cuts to a root of the problem.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Noonie</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> makes some plausible suggestions, but so far I like the recast delay, or something like it, the best.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Verant Representative:</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  As for CoD, yeah in my opinion it's a bit over powered right now. Not sure exactly what we're gonna do with it yet though.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->That means it is incumbent upon us to analyze the range of possible fixes, and highlight the best alternatives.<br>
<br>
Mages do not forget: the last big fix to charm had more effect on mages than charmers.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Yino:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  When some mages said...chanters said...Now some say...chanters are saying...Then they yell<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Like mages, enchanters do not speak with one voice.  As for charm, it is not just risk, but cost.  Managing risk, such as a charm break, is a cost.<br>
<br>
Thus I am reluctant to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;fix&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the risk of charm, as the result is unpredictable and unlikely to be balanced.  If the newer, higher level of risk is easily managed at a low cost, then the entire attempt to balance it is wasted.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Rahen:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  wouldn't capping the damage on the pet fix them from being overpowered? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Yes, but takes most of the can of whoopass out of the hands of enchanters, which would hurt and not be fun.<br>
<br>
In order to figure the magnitude of the fix, we need to have definitive information on the size of the problem.  We need more logs, more DPS figures, including down time.<br>
<br>
One idea that occured to me was to have mobs have some kind of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Willpower</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> factor, which charisma would help overcome, and the more willpower, the more the mob fought the charm while under control of another.  The net effect of this would be a slow, i.e., its heart is not into the fight.  Or such an effect could be limited only if the charmed mob shared faction with the mob it was ordered to fight.<br>
<br>
But I think making charmed pets less available by adding recast delay or its equivalent is the most elegant proposal so far.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Razamatazz Pizzazz</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
