ours on hours. They told us only really lazy chanters would use DC because its soo easy to keep one perma charmed<br>
<br>
Now some say regular charm is overpowered, chanters are saying its impossible to keep it perma charmed and is a huge risk to the group and them, and that they regularly have all kinds of problems and its not overpowered caus theres tons of risk...<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It's not hypocritical.  Command of Druzzil, Dire Charm and Boltran's Agacerie (level 54 charm spell) are 3 drastically different spells.<br>
<br>
I suppose the best way to explain it is to compare charming before PoP to charming with CoD.<br>
<br>
Using charm before PoP was significantly easier to do since Enchanters had a wider arsenol of spells to use that was a lot cheaper mana wise.  Most Enchanters would root the mob their pet was on.  This way when charm broke, only the pet would attack you.  Then you could shoot off a color stun (4-8 sec stun in 1-2sec casting time depending on which one you use) to stun the mob and recharm.  If the color stun is resisted, you can have more than one memorized and use another.  I don't want to make it sound like charming went off flawlessly before PoP, but it was significantly easier.<br>
<br>
Since PoP, Enchanters can no longer use stuns on mobs.  The best spell we get to do so is Word of Morrell which is a highly resisted 6.0 second mez type spell (which means it instantly breaks if the mob is mezzed).  If the mob resists WoM you have to wait 12.0 seconds to try again since there is no other spell that does the same thing.  Rooting the other mob is pretty much out of the question since most mobs in PoP summon which means instead of having the option of 1 mob on you, you'll likely have 2.<br>
<br>
PoP charming is also a lot more mana intensive.  Recharming with Boltran's costs 400mana while CoD costs 700.  Stunning with a color stun only costs about 40-60mana while WoM costs 300.  Bedlam (350dmg componentless rune) only cost 200mana to recast while Arcane Rune costs 400.  Even using a mezz for when the situation is out of hand costs a lot more (125mana vs. 275).<br>
<br>
So, that's basically why you have the change of heart from Enchanters where charm was once relatively easy and it now very risky.  A group can easily handle a level 54 add while one will likely head for the zone if they have an additional level 63 mob on them.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE HR START--><hr /><!--EZCODE HR END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> -The reason for this problem is one of their spell lines, charm, is broken. Charm, which is supposed to be situational in nature, is not situational.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Not to flame, but Verant has <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>never</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> to my knowledge once stated or even indicated this.  Any charm spell (excluding Dire Charm and Dictate) can be used repeatedly.  If you can point me to a resource where Verant said this, I'd love to see it.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Does the charm break put a huge aggro on the chanter?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yes.  In almost every case a mob that was charmed will head for the Enchanter.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Every pop zone i can think of has mobs in it specifically for the purpose of dire charm.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yes, plenty of PoP zones have mobs that can be DCed.  I think just about every Plane I've been to has had one.  Keep in mind though that a level 46 pet hitting a level 63ish mob will not do nearly as much damage as a level 46 pet could do on a level 55ish (average level mob in Luclin) mob. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://members.aol.com/nodnarbjh/csig.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
