 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=balanzsonofanz>Balanz son of Anz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Abuser of EZCodes</span><br>  Posts: 2513<br> <font color=#333333>(12/25/02 8:41:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=422.topic&index=39>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_exclamation_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Command of Druzzil, continued....</span><hr size=1> Look, I am reasonable man, and am reluctant to take away anyone's fun, but the more I read, the more it seems like there is a big problem.  Can anyone refute the following argument?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">If</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> only charming classes can sustain over 300 DPS,<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">and</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> charm entails only ordinary cost and risk,<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">and</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> charmed mobs are over twice the sustained DPS of non-charming damage dealers,<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">and</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> appropriate charmed mobs are generally available,<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">then</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> guilds, groups and raids will chose charmers to deal damage over all other damage dealing classes.<br>
<br>
Does this miss anything?  Is there a flaw in my reasoning?<br>
<br>
As I wrote earlier, in order to address this apparent problem, there are four factors that can be addressed:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Risk:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> How likely is it to result in death or wipeout?<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Cost:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> How much effort does it take to start and sustain it?<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Potency:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> How powerful are the charmed mobs?<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Applicability:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> How available are appropriate charmable mobs?<br>
<br>
Let me deal with these in turn.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Increased Risk:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Likely there is some room for increasing the risk associated with charm, especially if, as is claimed, the risk is currently ordinary and easily managed.  Some increase in risk seems justified and likely.  However, increased risk is unlikely to succeed at balancing charm.<br>
<br>
Risk versus reward is generally not well implemented in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>EverQuest</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  It is more of an ideal than a practice.  If <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Verant</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> decides to increase the risk, two results are likely.  Either the increased risk will be too little or be easily managed, not balancing charm at all, or the increased risk will be too much, and charm will be simply be abandoned.  In the latter case, enchanter's enjoyment of the game will be greatly reduced, as yet another strong technique will be taken from them with no compensation and a consequential narrowing of the role.<br>
<br>
Increased risk could come in the form of greater resists, more frequent breaks, or greater hate.<br>
<br>
I conclude that a modest but manageable increase in risk associated with charm will help to balance it without eliminating the technique.  It would be part of the solution rather than the whole though.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Increased Cost:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Managing increased risk increases the cost of the technique.  For example, if it took either two priests to support a single enchanter, or two enchanters and a priest to keep a powerful mob charmed, then it seems to me to be much more fair.  Taking three characters to do the damage of three damage dealers is much closer to fair than two characters.<br>
<br>
There are a number of ways to increase the cost.  Increase risk, increase mana cost, long recast delay <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(so that two enchanters might be required to maintain charm)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> are all fairly obvious ways to do this.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Decreased Potency:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The problem is the power of charmed mobs relative to player characters, especially in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Planes of Power</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Several suggestions have been made to lower the damage output of charmed mobs including a hard damage cap or slow <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(reflecting the mob's heart not being in the fight)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
The problem with decreasing potency is first, that if charmed mobs are too close in power to ordinary summoned pets, then the costs and risks of charm are not justified, and second, removing enchanters ability to whip out a can of spinach and punch <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Bluto</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> around for a while removes some fun from the game.  More than the damage itself is the issue of sustainability.  If a charmed mob can be easily maintained then it is summoned pets that become obsolete.<br>
<br>
I think it best to leave the damage output of charmed mobs alone, making it a high reward, and balance the risks and costs in other ways.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Reduced Availability:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
This I think is the key factor that is out of whack.  The reports I read here and elsewhere suggest that 300 DPS mobs are easily easily available and can be charmed indefinitely at modest cost and risk.  Thus a group consisting of one priest and five enchanters might enjoy the damage output of nearly three full groups without charmers.<br>
<br>
The obvious way to reduce the availability of charmable mobs is to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;flag&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> more mobs as being uncharmable.  However, if I were an enchanter, I think I would rather drown face first in a puddle of my own vomit then face yet another set of flagged mobs that were immune to my central abilities.  There are already plenty of mobs that immune to mezz, stun, and so on.  Flagged mobs are a brutal way to balance an ability, and enchanters have already seen more than their fair share of this.  While there are almost certainly some mobs that should not be charmable, that should be the rare exception rather than a common balance.<br>
<br>
So far, I like the ideas that force a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;gap&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> between the expiration of the charm and its recast.  Several authors have suggested increasing the recast delay on the best charms that is longer than the maximum duration of the charm.  That way, when charm breaks, the mob cannot simply be recharmed, but must be dealt with by some other means.  In this case it would take two enchanters to keep a strong mob continuously charmed.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Noonie</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> suggested putting a timer on the charmer, like the user of a rod, that prevented them from charming again until it expired.  This acts something like a recast delay, but is even more limiting.  I am not sure this is necessary, and would not allow an enchanter to alternate lower level charms where appropriate.<br>
<br>
Alternately, the expiration of a charm could trigger a short buff on the mob that prevents anyone from recharming it for a short while after it breaks.  This would prevent multiple chanters from keeping a mob charmed, which might be too much of a limitation.<br>
<br>
Remember, the goal is to solve the problem while preserving as much of everyone's capabilities as possible.<br>
<br>
Yes, the preceding discussion does appear to assume that a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;nerf&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of some kind is the only solution, but I would dearly love to see an alternative that did not reduce charm's power in some way.  By my rough estimate, the output of other damage dealing classes would have to be doubled in order for non-charmers to compete with charmers for the role of damage dealer.  And even then the other abilities a charmer would bring to a group would leave player melees out in the cold.  A doubling of player damage output would likely break much more than it would fix.<br>
<br>
It is still not conclusively established that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Command of Druzzil</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> allows a supported enchanter to deal damage comparable to three ordinary damage dealing characters.  There are also likely many possible solutions that have not yet been suggested.<br>
<br>
But keep in mind that a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;fix&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> will likely hurt as much as it helps, and may not even remedy the problem in question.  Also, enchanters have already had more than their share of having their central abilities limited in arbitrary ways such as flagged mobs.<br>
<br>
We must be careful in what we propose, and thorough in our analysis.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Razamatazz Pizzazz</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
